  "editorial": {
    "headline": "Jazz Chisholm Jr. Homer Breaks Open Rivalry for New York",
    "subheadline": "New York Yankees beats Boston Red Sox.",
    "lead_angle": "Jazz Chisholm Jr. broke open a tense rivalry at Yankee Stadium, launching a three-run home run in the bottom of the eighth inning. The blast cemented a late surge for the New York Yankees, who defeated the Boston Red Sox by a score of 6-1. It was Chisholm Jr.’s only hit of the afternoon, but it provided ample cushion as the Yankees sealed a crucial division victory.\n\nThe contest remained tight through seven frames, with both teams managing a single run. Paul Goldschmidt put the New York Yankees on the board first in the fifth, singling home a run to snap a scoreless tie. The Boston Red Sox countered in the sixth when Jarren Duran crossed the plate, knotting the score at one. However, the eighth inning saw the Yankees explode. After Cody Bellinger smacked a solo shot to give New York a lead, a walk and a single set the stage for Chisholm Jr.'s decisive three-run bomb, opening a significant gap that Boston could not close.\n\nChisholm Jr.'s 1-for-4 performance with three runs batted in highlighted several strong Yankee offensive efforts. Cody Bellinger finished 2-for-4, including his solo home run, while Trent Grisham collected three hits in four at-bats and an RBI. Paul Goldschmidt also added a 2-for-4 day with an RBI. Tim Hill collected the victory in relief for the New York Yankees. Justin Slaten was tagged with the loss for the Boston Red Sox. This division matchup holds significant weight in the American League East standings, as the Yankees look to extend their lead against a struggling Red Sox squad vying for a wild card spot.",
